    <h1>RNA Seq Pipeline</h1>

    <a href="https://arthur-huan.github.io/course-tree">Live Website</a>
    <a href="httsp://github.com/arthur-huan/CourseTree">GitHub (technical writeup)</a>

    <p class="note">
      CourseTree is a full-stack web application that transforms a university course catalog into an interactive academic planning tool. The project combines a Python data processing pipeline with a React and TypeScript frontend to convert unstructured course descriptions into structured prerequisite data that students can explore visually. Rather than navigating static catalog pages, users can browse hundreds of courses simultaneously, receive live prerequisite validation while building a course plan, and switch between complementary grid and graph-based visualizations that remain synchronized through a shared application state.
    </p>

    <p class="note">
      The backend focuses on extracting structured information from inconsistent natural-language course descriptions. Using Python, spaCy, Pandas, and Pydantic, the pipeline normalizes catalog data, identifies course references, and reconstructs complex prerequisite logic expressed through free-form text. Because standard boolean expressions cannot represent requirements such as "two courses from..." or "six credit hours from...", the parser outputs a custom domain-specific language that extends postfix notation with additional operators capable of modeling the full range of prerequisite structures found in the university catalog.
    </p>

    <p class="note">
      The frontend was built with React, TypeScript, Zustand, React Flow, and Tailwind CSS, with an emphasis on responsiveness and scalability. A high-density grid view displays over 100 courses simultaneously while providing real-time feedback on prerequisite satisfaction, planning conflicts, and course status. An accompanying directed acyclic graph (DAG) view visualizes prerequisite relationships using automatically generated layouts and custom edge routing to improve readability in densely connected graphs. Both interfaces consume the same centralized state store, ensuring selections, filters, and planning decisions remain synchronized without duplicating application state.
    </p>

    <p class="note">
      The project presented two major engineering challenges. The first was parsing inconsistent natural-language prerequisite descriptions into a structured representation suitable for computation. University course catalogs express requirements using varying sentence structures, nested boolean logic, and constructs such as course pools and credit-based requirements that cannot be modeled with conventional AND/OR expressions alone. I addressed this by combining spaCy's NLP capabilities with rule-based parsing and a custom domain-specific language capable of representing the full range of prerequisite structures. A second challenge was visualizing these relationships as a readable directed acyclic graph (DAG). Standard graph layouts and edge routing become difficult to interpret in densely connected prerequisite networks, so I implemented layered graph layouts and custom edge routing based on node geometry to clearly communicate prerequisite hierarchies while maintaining an interactive user experience.
    </p>
  </main>
</BaseLayout>
